eceased","1425":"1425","1512":"1512","1424":"1424","1400":"1400","about 1424":"about 1424","1450":"1450","1449":"1449","about 1450":"about 1450","of Dalegarth, Cumberland, England":"Dalegarth, Cumberland, England, United Kingdom","Dalegarth, Cumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Dalegarth, Cumberland, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Stanley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Stanley, including those in Yorkshire, Staffordshire, Derbyshire, Durham, Gloucestershire, and Wiltshire, named with Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone, rock’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. This English name has been established in Ireland since the 13th century where it was Gaelicized as <b>de Stainléigh</b>.","English: possibly also a variant of <b>Stoneley</b>, a habitational name from Stoneley Green in Burland (Cheshire), Stoneleigh (Warwickshire), or Stonely in Kimbolton (Huntingdonshire), all named with Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone, rock’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","Americanized form of any of various like-sounding names in other languages, for example Polish   Stanislawski  , Greek   Anastasiou  , and Serbian <b>Stojadinov</b> (patronymic from the personal name <i>Stojadin</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Stanislawski","meanings":["Polish (<b>Stanisławski</b>): habitational name for someone from any of various places called Stanisław, Stanisławów, or Stanisławice, named with the personal name <i>Stanisław</i> (see   Stanislav  )."]},{"name":"Standley","meanings":["English: variant of   Stanley  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form